benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: GET /1.0/kb/customFields/{customFieldId}/auditLogsWithHistory - Retrieve custom field audit logs with history by id

covered: Valid request: success path covered (TC01) — endpoint returns 200 and Content-Type application/json with a JSON array of AuditLog objects.
AuditLog schema: TC01 asserts returned AuditLog objects contain required fields (schema/shape validation).
Empty response handling: TC02 and TC12 verify the API returns an empty JSON array when no audit logs exist and covers a prior regression.
404 error cases: TC03 and TC04 cover non-existent custom field and missing associated Account returning 404 with an error message.
Path parameter validation: TC05 (invalid format) and TC16 (UUID boundary values) validate handling of malformed and boundary customFieldId values.
Authentication: TC06 and TC07 cover missing and invalid authentication tokens returning 401.
Server error handling: TC08 simulates backend/database unavailability and expects 503 service unavailable.
Security: TC09 checks SQL injection payload handling and ensures no internal stack traces are exposed.
Malformed/edge path cases: TC10, TC15, and TC17 cover extra path segments, missing customFieldId, and leading/trailing spaces.
Performance and scale: TC11 tests very large result sets and TC14 covers concurrent requests/performance behavior and thresholds.
Regression and compatibility: TC12 verifies prior non-JSON regression is fixed and TC13 checks backward compatibility with older User-Agent headers.
gaps: Pagination: No tests cover pagination, page size limits, out-of-range pages, or server behavior if the API were to paginate large result sets.
Rate limiting/throttling: There are no tests exercising rate limits (429 responses, Retry-After header) or behavior under sustained request bursts.
Caching behavior: No tests for caching headers (ETag, Cache-Control, Last-Modified) or conditional GET semantics (304 Not Modified).
Authorization scopes/permissions (403): Tests cover unauthenticated (401) cases but not authenticated-but-forbidden scenarios (403) or role/permission checks.
Structured error schema: Tests assert presence of an error message but do not validate a consistent error payload schema (error code, type, fields) for programmatic clients.
Content negotiation / Accept header handling: No tests for different Accept headers or 406/format negotiation behavior.
recommendations: Add pagination tests if the API supports/should support paging: verify limit/offset or page token behavior, total counts, and correct responses for out-of-range pages; if the API intentionally returns all items, document that and add tests asserting behavior for extremely large result sets (streaming/chunking).
Add rate limiting tests: generate bursts of requests to verify 429 responses, Retry-After header semantics, and graceful degradation under enforced limits.
Add caching tests: check ETag, Cache-Control, Last-Modified headers; include conditional GET tests that expect 304 when resource has not changed.
Add permission/authorization tests for 403 cases: verify authenticated tokens lacking required scopes/roles receive 403 and that privileged tokens can access data.
Validate structured error responses: assert a consistent error schema (errorCode, message, details) and that no sensitive/internal info is leaked in error payloads.
Add content negotiation tests: verify behavior for various Accept headers and that Content-Type for responses matches Accept or returns appropriate 406 responses.
Expand negative/fuzz tests: include long/overly-large path segments, unexpected unicode, URL-encoded inputs and confirm server handles them safely.
Add precise performance/load benchmarks and automate verification of response-time SLAs for large datasets and concurrency; integrate these into CI or a performance test suite.
